  "prompt": "How are rain scenes shot in movies?",
  "response": "Rain scenes in movies are shot using various techniques:\n\n1. Rain Towers/Rain Bars\n- Large scaffolding-like structures with pipes and nozzles\n- Positioned above the scene to create controlled rainfall\n- Water pressure and nozzle design control rain intensity and pattern\n\n2. Water Trucks\n- Large trucks with high-pressure water systems\n- Spray water onto the scene from multiple angles\n- Used for street or exterior scenes\n\n3. Special Rain Machines\n- Smaller, more precise water distribution systems\n- Can be handheld or mounted on stands\n- Used for close-up or specific area shots\n\n4. Practical Effects\n- Blue or green screens with water effects added digitally in post-production\n- Useful for complex or dangerous rain scenes\n\n5. Glycerin or Special Solutions\n- Used to make water droplets look more cinematic\n- Creates more defined and dramatic water droplets\n- Helps water stick to actors and surfaces better\n\n6. Digital Effects\n- Computer-generated rain added in post-production\n- Used when practical effects are impractical or too expensive\n\n7. Backlit Rain\n- Positioning lights behind water streams\n- Creates more dramatic and visible rain effect\n\nCinematographers choose techniques based on budget, scene requirements, and desired visual effect.",
